S'I think that there\xe2\x80\x99s a willingness to believe the worst about Israel in some quarters of Europe, and that\xe2\x80\x99s something that has been part of our history in Europe for many generations. People believed outrageous things about the Jewish people, as some now believe about the Jewish state. What is our great crime? What is it we\xe2\x80\x99re doing? We\xe2\x80\x99re building in the areas that will remain in a final peace settlement of Israel. This is not some foreign land. This is the land in which the Jewish people have been for close to 4000 years.What we\xe2\x80\x99re talking about is suburbs contiguous to Jerusalem. And everybody knows that they will remain part of Israel. You don\xe2\x80\x99t change the map, you don\xe2\x80\x99t prejudge anything. I think there is heightened sensitivity. I didn\xe2\x80\x99t see this heightened sensitivity from some of these governments when the Palestinians violated the Oslo Accords. I didn\xe2\x80\x99t see them speaking out when President Abbas claimed solidarity with the Hamas terrorists who are rocketing Israel. I didn\xe2\x80\x99t see it when they speak now of a union between Hamas and the Palestinian Authority. I don\xe2\x80\x99t hear that and I don\xe2\x80\x99t think that this is conducive to peace. I think it\xe2\x80\x99s counterproductive.I think the one-sided criticism of Israel just tells the Palestinians that they can get away with violating their solemn pledges for peace, and I don\xe2\x80\x99t think it advances peace. Israel is prepared to have peace with a Palestinian state. The Palestinians want a Palestinian state without peace. Many of these European governments who voted for this thinking it may advance peace but in fact this pushes peace backwards because it tells the Palestinians you can get international recognition and international legitimacy without making the necessary compromises for peace.'
