S' If you\xe2\x80\x99ve been in battle it is not something you would want to repeat. It\xe2\x80\x99s not a pleasant experience. I myself was wounded, as you say, in a rescue effort of the hijacked Sabina airplane. First of all, it\xe2\x80\x99s not a particularly pleasant thing to be wounded by gunfire. And also, it\xe2\x80\x99s tragic to lose a brother, as I did, or a husband, or a father, or a son. Anybody who\xe2\x80\x99s been through war does their utmost to prevent war. That is something that is very, very strong, and that is why before I decide on military action, I think very carefully about the consequences. That\xe2\x80\x99s something that is very deeply ingrained.On the other hand, we also have the knowledge that if once again we become defenseless, we won\xe2\x80\x99t exist. We had no defenses before the establishment of the Jewish state, and we could be tossed like a leaf in the wind. And we were incinerated like refuse. And so the Jewish state was established, among other things, to give the Jewish people a home in their ancestral homeland, but also to give them the capacity for self-defense. Our enemies who know that they cannot defeat us on the battlefield in legitimate warfare, are using two types of weapons against us: the weapon of terror \xe2\x80\x93 rockets fired on our cities. And the weapon of lies. To describe Israel as a mighty Goliath when in fact, it\xe2\x80\x99s a David facing so many challenges from every direction, by people who are committed to our destruction.We don\xe2\x80\x99t seek to destroy them. We don\xe2\x80\x99t seek to destroy the Palestinians. We seek to live in peace with them. We don\xe2\x80\x99t use a fraction of our power because we have constraints on the use of military force. If you\xe2\x80\x99re a soldier, you know those constraints, and I do as a former soldier. But the difference is this: we seek to live in peace with our neighbors, and they seek to either eradicate us with a frontal attack, or to establish a state that will not live in peace with us. And either one is unacceptable. There is no one in Israel who wants peace more than me. I\xe2\x80\x99ve seen the tragedy of war, and I know the blessings of peace. But to achieve peace you have to have a partner that is willing to sit down and negotiate. And so far, I have not been able to get such a partner. For four years, I\xe2\x80\x99ve been calling on President Abbas to sit down and negotiate. For four years, he\xe2\x80\x99s run away from responding to that call, and in fact, he just did that again by going to the UN.'
